 it has been adopted for   Woulfe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woulfe","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname (  see  Wolf  ), sometimes used as a first name in honour of the Irish rebel  Theobald Wolfe Tone  (  see  Tone  ) or the English  General James Wolfe  (  1727–59 ), who died at the Battle of Quebec."]},{"name":"Wooley","meanings":["English: variant of   Woolley  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":2,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":96,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":105,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Woolley of Dorset was born in 1453, in Broadbottom, Cheshire, England, his father, John de Woley, was 58 and his mother, Joane Kriton, was 58. He married Mrs. John Woolley in 1480, in Mottram in Longdendale, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1453–":"1453–Surnud","1450–1542":"1450–1542","1453–Male":"1453–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1396":"1396","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1542":"1542","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","BEF. 1434":"enne 1434","1549":"1549","Broadbottom, Cheshire, England":"Broadbottom, Cheshire, England","Leigh, Dorset, England":"Leigh, Dorset, England","Mottram in Longdendale, Cheshire, England":"Mottram in Longdendale, Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1453–":"1453–Kuollut","1450–1542":"1450–1542","1453–Male":"1453–Kuollut","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","1485–Male":"1485–Kuollut","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1396–Female":"1396–Kuollut","1396":"1396","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1542":"1542","1453":"1453","1485":"1485","BEF. 1434":"ennen vuotta 1434","1549":"1549","Broadbottom, Cheshire, England":"Broadbottom, Cheshire, England","Leigh, Dorset, England":"Leigh, Dorset, England","Mottram in Longdendale, Cheshire, England":"Mottram in Longdendale, Cheshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1453–":"1453–Décédé","1450–1542":"1450–1542","1453–Male":"1453–Décédé","1460–Female":"1460–Décédée","1485–Male":"1485–Décédé","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1396–Female":"1396–Décédée","1396":"1396","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1455":"1455","1542":"1542","145